50|$|<b>Pygmy</b> <b>falcons</b> {{occasionally}} {{engage in}} polyandrous relationships, {{where there are}} more than two adults living together and tending nestlings. There are four potential reasons for this behaviour: defence, co-operative polyandry, delayed dispersal of offspring, and thermoregulation (warmth). Corroboration for the last is that in winter African <b>pygmy</b> <b>falcons</b> nest further inside the nest of sociable weavers, where there is better insulation.|$|R
